#### Feature Description

It would be very useful if there is a service e.g. `CDKScrollableManager` that returns a `CDKScrollable` reference for the given scrollable element

#### Use Case

In my case, I have a custom scrollbar library, the `CDKScrollable` directive is used in the default viewport element, however, the problem occurred when I wanted to make it possible for users to use their own custom scroll viewport.

This is very important for integrating other libraries like `ngx-infinite-scroll` or `CDKVirtualScroll` along with the custom scrollbar library

_Example of integrating_

```html
<lib-component>
  <div infiniteScroll libCustomViewPort>
     content...
  </div>
</lib-component>

OR

<lib-component>
  <cdk-virtual-scroll-viewport libCustomViewPort>
     content...
  </div>
</lib-component>
```

In the custom scrollbar library, the component template has something like this

```html
<div class="ng-scroll-viewport-wrapper">
   <div #viewport>
       <ng-content></ng-content>
   </div>
</div>
<scrollbar-control *ngIf="verticalScrollbarUsed" ..>
<scrollbar-control *ngIf="horizontalScrollbarUsed" ..>
```
In the component code I want to be able to set the `CDKScrollable` on a projected content element if user used the library's custom viewport directive

```ts
export class LibComponent {

  @ViewChild('viewport', { static: true }) defaultViewport: ElementRef;
  @ContentChild(LibCustomViewPort, { static: true }) customViewport: LibCustomViewPort;
  scrollableRef: CDKScrollable;

  // Assume this service exists
  constructor(private manager: CDKScrollableManager) {
  }

  ngOnInit() {
     if (this.customViewPort) {
         // If user used the custom viewport directive
         this.scrollableRef = this.manager.getCDKScrollable(this.customViewport.nativeElement);
     } else {
         this.scrollableRef = this.manager.getCDKScrollable(this.defaultViewport.nativeElement);
     }
  }
}
```

But since this `CDKScrollable` is only provided as a directive, users of my library who want to use a custom viewport will have to import the `ScrollingModule` and also add the `CDKScrollable` directive along with `libCustomViewPort` directive, which kinda ruins the library's goal to ease the usage.
